the date of the notice.
Proposed law changes the time period to pay the assessment, appeal to the BTA for a
redetermination, or pay under protest and file suit or a petition from sixty days to ninety days
and otherwise retains present law.
Present law allows a taxpayer sixty days from the date of payment or posting bond to appeal
to the BTA for a redetermination of the assessment when the tax is in jeopardy and property
has been distrained.
Proposed law changes the time period to appeal to the BTA for a redetermination of the
assessment when the tax is in jeopardy and property has been distrained from sixty days to
ninety days.
Present law allows a taxpayer sixty days from the date of the notice of assessment from the
Department of Revenue to either pay the amount of the assessment or to appeal to the BTA
for a redetermination.
Proposed law changes the time period to either pay the amount of the assessment or to
appeal to the BTA for a redetermination from sixty days to ninety days.
Present law allows a taxpayer sixty days after the Department of Revenue disallows a refund
claim to appeal the disallowance with the BTA.
Proposed law changes the time period to appeal the disallowance of the refund claim from
sixty days to ninety days.
Effective August 1, 2026.
